y/waters area|Kuortane}}|km2|abbr=on}} is water.<ref name=\"total_area\" /> The [[population density]] is {{convert|{{Infobox Finnish municipality/population density|Kuortane|round=2}}|PD/km2}}.\n[[File:Kuortane church 2012.jpg|250px|thumbnail|right|Old church in Kuortane]]\nThe municipality is unilingually [[Finnish language|Finnish]].\n\nKuortane is the birthplace of world-famous architect [[Alvar Aalto]].\n\nKuortane has a notable history of pine tar production. It is currently well known for the [[Kuortaneen urheilulukio]], a sports institute and training facility where many young Finnish athletes study and train. Both the [[Finland women's national under-18 ice hockey team|women's national under-18 ice hockey team]] and [[Team Kuortane]] of the [[Naisten Liiga (ice hockey)|Naisten Liiga]] are based at the institute.\n\n==People==\n* [[Alvar Aalto]] (1898\u20131976), architect and designer\n* [[Osmo Ala-Honkola]] (born 1939), Olympic sport shooter\n* [[Reino Ala-Kulju]] (1898\u20131983), Lutheran clergyman, politician, and teacher\n* [[Mira Suhonen]] (born 1985), Olympic sport shooter\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kuortaneen urheilulukio]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Kuortane}}\n*[http://www.kuortane.fi/ Municipality of Kuortane] \u2013 Official website {{in lang|fi}}\n\n{{SouthernOstrobothnia}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Southern Ostrobothnia]]\n[[Category:Kuortane| ]]\n\n\n{{WesternFinland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Finnish municipality\n|name                   = Kuortane\n|official_name          = {{lang|fi|Kuortaneen kunta}}<br />{{lang|sv|Kuortane kommun}}\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \n|native_name_lang       = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Municipality <!-- City, Town or Municipality-->\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  = \n|image